","body":"In 1682 John Wilson preached in New Haven for over a year. Col. John Dixwell — one of the English regicides then living in hiding in New Haven — wrote to Rev. Increase Mather calling him \"a veire hopefull yonge man of good abilities.\" Wilson returned to Medfield in 1684 and eventually abandoned the ministry."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Left Harvard — his father taught him everything","body":"He left Harvard College soon after admission, but received a thorough private education from his father in divinity, medicine, and law. He settled in Braintree in 1692 and spent the rest of his life farming, practicing medicine, and performing legal services."},{"number":3,"category":"marriage","header":"Married his first cousin — both Hooker grandchildren","body":"His mother was Sarah Hooker Wilson (Thomas Hooker's daughter); his wife Sarah Newton's mother was Mary Hooker Newton (also Thomas Hooker's daughter). The two mothers were sisters. EH and the Wilson genealogy both explicitly note the cousin relationship."}],"career":[{"role":"Schoolmaster","organization":"Town of Medfield","end_year":1692,"notes":"Employed as schoolmaster in Medfield for several terms; also assisted father in ministry."},{"role":"Representative","organization":"Massachusetts General Court","start_year":1698,"end_year":1698,"notes":"Representative from Braintree, 1698."},{"role":"Justice of the Peace","organization":"Braintree, Massachusetts","start_year":1700,"notes":"Commission June 7, 1700. Held until death."}],"military_service":[{"rank":"Captain","unit":"Local militia company, Braintree","rank_year_start":1696,"notes":"Commission as captain of one of the local military companies, 1696."}],"bio":{"display_name":"John Wilson","first_name":"John","last_name":"Wilson","married_names":[]},"documents":[],"artworks":[],"slug":"john-wilson-1660"},"H00016":{"id":"H00016","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas